#: 6ffc5a3e42204665884b09f9038710e3
msgid ""
"Conceptually the element layer answers one question: *given a weak form "
"to integrate over a mesh, where are the quadrature points, what are the "
"shape-function values and gradients there, and what is the integration "
"weight?* It does this by composing seven static reference-element "
"definitions with the physical-space connectivity of your mesh. The "
"overall flow is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:151
#: ee87bf2e68b3422484137064282f463e
msgid ""
"The rest of this section walks through every box and shows what the "
"returned tensors actually look like. All examples use "
":class:`~tensormesh.Triangle` because it is the cheapest to print, but "
"the structure is identical for the other six shapes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:158
#: ec4d2075a6904e949f1ef5d69d15aa29
msgid "Step 0 — Reference-element topology"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:160
#: d84d56c74a6b419188ec48c477eb8774
msgid ""
"Each subclass carries a handful of class-level ``torch.Tensor`` / "
"``tuple`` attributes that pin down the reference geometry. Nothing here "
"depends on ``order`` — these are just the corners of the reference shape "
"and how they connect:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:182
#: 9c66f8eec76b48319ba7c43e58a699b3
msgid ""
"Two derived attributes worth knowing about: "
":attr:`~tensormesh.Element.is_mix_facet` is ``True`` for "
":class:`~tensormesh.Prism` and :class:`~tensormesh.Pyramid` (whose facets"
" come in two shapes), and otherwise ``False``; "
":meth:`~tensormesh.Element.get_facet_type` returns the facet element "
"class (``Line`` for a triangle, ``Triangle`` for a tetrahedron, the tuple"
" ``(Triangle, Quadrilateral)`` for a prism)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:192
#: 1bfdc04f72d5402e9f460e3ef29cdefd
msgid "Step 1 — Lagrange nodes (``get_basis``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:194
#: 3afae80dae144554a84381af96bda538
msgid ""
":meth:`~tensormesh.Element.get_basis` picks where the interpolation nodes"
" sit on the reference element for a given polynomial order. The "
"convention is *vertex nodes first, then edge nodes, then face/interior "
"nodes* — see :ref:`node-ordering-gallery` for the visual companion across"
" all seven shapes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:214
#: 15852e01c5794befbb013fcd047b176b
msgid ""
"The output shape is ``[N_b, D]`` with :math:`N_b = (p+1)(p+2)/2` for "
"simplex shapes and :math:`(p+1)^d` for tensor-product shapes (quad / "
"hex). Every other step in the pipeline indexes into this layout, so it is"
" the single source of truth for \"what does *basis function b* mean?\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:221
#: 6b643eb198404c379ced06a3e5619ab0
msgid "Step 2 — Polynomial space (``get_polynomial``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:223
#: c1db5a0fc0c34d31b883811830f6e5ce
msgid ""
":meth:`~tensormesh.Element.get_polynomial` returns the polynomial space "
"the shape functions live in, as a "
":class:`~tensormesh.element.Polynomial`. The space depends on the shape: "
"simplex elements use the full :math:`P_k` (terms with total degree "
":math:`\\le k`); tensor-product elements use :math:`Q_k` (each coordinate"
" exponent :math:`\\le k`); pyramid and prism use their own ad-hoc spaces."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:238
#: f4711c14a0a94ce1a7481b4d96472596
msgid ""
"You usually never call this directly — "
":meth:`~tensormesh.Element.get_basis_fns` invokes it for you. The hook is"
" meant to be overridden by people adding a new element type, so that the "
"base class can synthesise the Lagrange basis on top of a custom "
"polynomial space."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:245
#: 347c6a79d5db4069b3d56c1d5eb1793c
msgid "Step 3 — Hat functions (``get_basis_fns``, ``get_basis_grad_fns``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:247
#: 3ac893771ccc4afaba7595417b16b49e
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
":meth:`~tensormesh.Element.get_basis_fns` combines the previous two — "
"Lagrange nodes plus polynomial space — into the basis function set. "
"Internally TensorMesh evaluates the polynomial-space terms at the basis "
"nodes, inverts the resulting Vandermonde matrix, and pushes the "
"coefficients into a :class:`~tensormesh.element.Polynomials` (batched "
"polynomial) object. The output satisfies the Lagrange property "
":math:`\\phi_b(\\boldsymbol{\\xi}_{b'}) = \\delta_{bb'}`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:273
#: d1f47f95b1fa4c1ea1dbaa830058d0fd
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The result of :meth:`~tensormesh.Element.get_basis_fns` is **mesh-"
"independent** — every element in the mesh, regardless of physical shape, "
"uses the same :math:`\\phi_b(\\boldsymbol{\\xi})`. This is the entire "
"point of the reference-element trick."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:278
#: cf027145b76e467aabd99450312699a7
msgid "P1 triangle shape functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:282
#: 10028f9dc6164617adf22becb7c7da47
msgid ""
"The three P1 shape functions on the reference triangle. Each "
":math:`\\phi_b` equals 1 at vertex *b* (red marker) and decays linearly "
"to 0 at the other two vertices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:286
#: 651b0eedd5764a479f05ee38950499d9
msgid ""
"For higher-order surface plots on every supported shape, see "
":doc:`/example_gallery/basics` (section \"Shape functions\"). Internally "
"the example_gallery scripts call exactly the "
":meth:`~tensormesh.Element.get_basis_fns` you just saw — there is no "
"separate plotting code path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:294
#: b502aa912f824d1287e9e503197c5511
msgid "Step 4 — Reference quadrature (``get_quadrature``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:296
#: 5186e853737741099b0bf3e53f96edab
msgid ""
":meth:`~tensormesh.Element.get_quadrature` returns a Gauss-type rule on "
"the reference element — weights of shape ``[N_q]`` and points of shape "
"``[N_q, D]``. The ``order`` argument is the *quadrature order*, not the "
"basis order; pick it large enough to integrate your weak form exactly. As"
" a rule of thumb, ``quadrature_order = 2 * basis_order`` is enough for "
"most bilinear forms on Laplace-type problems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:311
#: 916e42bf05fe4d66a450b3f1f28c7cc2
msgid ""
"Triangle, quad, hex, tet, pyramid, prism each pick a different rule "
"family; see ``tensormesh/element/quadrature.py`` for the tables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:316
#: a6df2b775da94d4db9ae31c78b341611
msgid "Step 5 — Reference shape values (``eval_shape_val``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:318
#: c2ea9393a927425ca65a0613a7e44872
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
":meth:`~tensormesh.Element.eval_shape_val` composes Step 3 (basis "
"functions) with Step 4 (quadrature points): the resulting matrix has "
"entry :math:`[q, b] = \\phi_b(\\boldsymbol{\\xi}_q)`. This is still "
"purely reference-element data — no mesh has been touched."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:333
#: e0a0d423297d41e3bf6f0adc5787de62
msgid ""
"Every element of every mesh, no matter its physical shape, reuses this "
"single :math:`[N_q, N_b]` matrix. This is the source of the FEM speed-up "
"over collocation methods — you build it once and broadcast it across all "
"elements during assembly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:340
#: b7c7047441ff4ead8690d15838e3d9e0
msgid "Step 6 — Cell Jacobian and physical gradients"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:342
#: a8373b73bf714ed8b31b56e32c798758
msgid "Now the mesh enters. For each element :math:`e`, the isoparametric map"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:344
#: 65be2dbe08ce49af95a0cea5319e3195
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"\\mathbf{x}^e(\\boldsymbol{\\xi}) \\;=\\; \\sum_{b=1}^{N_b}\n"
"      \\phi_b(\\boldsymbol{\\xi})\\, \\mathbf{x}^e_b"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:349
#: 545ee1297a3048448e14b1063ddab407
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"sends the reference element :math:`\\hat K` to the physical element "
":math:`K^e`, where :math:`\\mathbf{x}^e_b` are the physical coordinates "
"of element *e*'s basis nodes. Its Jacobian :math:`\\mathbf{J}^e_q = "
"\\partial \\mathbf{x}^e / \\partial \\boldsymbol{\\xi}`, evaluated at "
"quadrature point :math:`q`, is"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:355
#: d586a7e6f8e04eeb817f3567334a2dd0
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"J^e_{q,ij} \\;=\\; \\sum_{b=1}^{N_b}\n"
"      (\\mathbf{x}^e_b)_j \\, \\frac{\\partial \\phi_b}{\\partial \\xi_i}"
"\n"
"      (\\boldsymbol{\\xi}_q)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:361
#: db7eded165974693b43675518063189d
msgid ""
":meth:`~tensormesh.Element.eval_cell_jacobian` computes exactly this sum "
"across the whole mesh:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:382
#: be5b684424464d699bff8d50e6130611
msgid ""
"Physical-space gradients of the shape functions are then obtained by the "
"chain rule :math:`\\nabla_{\\!x}\\phi_b = "
"\\mathbf{J}^{-T}\\nabla_{\\!\\xi}\\phi_b`, which "
":meth:`~tensormesh.Element.eval_shape_grad` packages together with the "
"Jacobian it had to compute anyway:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:402
#: 801dbff8b92c440785665c626496353d
msgid ""
"This is the first place in the pipeline where the **physical "
"coordinates** ``element_coords`` enter. Everything before this point "
"(``get_basis``, ``get_basis_fns``, ``eval_shape_val``) was pure "
"reference-element data; everything after it depends on the mesh geometry."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:408
#: 3c8439fb338d4e8ca7a4f953b054a354
msgid "Reference triangle vs physical triangle, with mapped quadrature points"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:412
#: fd86fe2daeb44d228265b1bde27feade
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Step 6 visualised on a single triangle. Left: reference element "
":math:`\\hat K` with its three order-2 Gauss points. Right: a stretched, "
"translated physical triangle :math:`K`. The Gauss points are mapped "
"through the isoparametric map :math:`\\mathbf{F}_K`; values "
":math:`\\phi_b(\\boldsymbol{\\xi}_q)` reused unchanged from Step 5 are "
"now tied to the physical points :math:`\\mathbf{x}_q` for integration. "
"The Jacobian :math:`\\mathbf{J}` of this map drives both the gradient "
"transform and the :math:`\\lvert\\det\\mathbf{J}\\rvert` volume factor in"
" the next step."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:424
#: 8ad69b6d6ac24773909c6059cffff608
msgid "Step 7 — ``Transformation``: the cached package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/elements_and_quadrature.rst:426
#: e91bb5e5d1d34fc49c8c7bbd7eb787bc
msgid ""
"In practice you never call ``eval_*`` directly. Instead you instantiate a"
" :class:`~tensormesh.Transformation`, which lazily wires together every "
"step of the pipeline and caches the results as :class:`torch.nn.Module` "
"buffers (so ``.to(device)`` / ``.double()`` / ``.cuda()`` Just Work)."
msgstr ""

